RESOURCES\
\
\
Pod\
- is the layer of compute, is the substitute for a VM, runs one or more containers which are isolated proceses\
- has an IP address\
- one or more volumes, (emptyDir\{\} is common to all containers in the pod)\
- virtual environment which creates shared networking and filesystem space for one or more containers\
- containers within a pod can communicate with each other using the localhost address\
- containers withina a pod can communicate with each other using IPC if shareProcessNamespace is set to true\
- is not ready until all containers in a pod are not ready\
\
- containers are provided a token to communicate with API SERVER???\
\
\
ReplicaSet	\
- supports set-based selector requirements\
\
Note: Don\'92t use this directly, use Deployment object\
\
\
\
Deployment\
- Uses a ReplicaSet\
- does not support life cycle hooks just yet (when reading version 4)\
- scaling a deployment means it updates the existing ReplicaSet, changing the pod spec means it replaces the existing ReplicaSet with a new one\
- pod/s name contains a hash of the template in the pod spec for deployment, so if you make a change to the spec which matches a previous deployment then it will have the same template\
  hash as a previous deployment\
- Deployment adds labels of the pod to the replicaset\
- Deployments retain 10 replicasets by default\
- Strategies for deployment are \
  - recreate		-	terminate the old version then release the new one [USE CASE - different versions of the app can\'92t coexist]\
  - ramped 		-	release a new version in a rolling update fashion (DEFAULT), scale down old replicaset while scaling up new replicaset, provides service continuity and staggering\
  - blue/green 		-	release a new version alongside an old version, then switch traffic\
  - canary			-	release a new version to a subset of users, then proceed to a full rollout\
  - a/b testing		-	release a new version to a subset of user in a precise way (HTTP headers, cookie, weight, etc.), a techniques for making business decisions based on stats, does not come out of the box with k8s\
- Deployments do not replace pods that leave the ready state when a probe fails\
\
\
\
\
Endpoints\
\
\
\
\
Namespaces\
- boundary to apply security and resource restrictions\
- pods in different namespaces can communicate through services\
- a controller looks for pods only its own namespace\
\
\
