Services\
- is the virtualization for the network\
- a service only sends traffic to pods which are Ready\
\
\
ClusterIP			-		cluster wide IP address for the service\
						the service can be accessed by name by a pod on any node, kube-dns will return the IP to the pod\
						only works within the cluster, so only for communicating between pods\
						a selector is mandatory when defining the service\
						CluserIP ---> Pod\
\
NodePort			-		\cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
asks Kubernetes to open a static port in every cluster node on a high port between 30,000 and 32,767 (by default). It is exposed on the IP of each node and is automatically routed to a ClusterIP Service that is created for it.
\f1\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 \
						
\f0\fs24 \cf0 \cb1 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 NodePort services don\'92t require an external load balancer						every node in the cluster listens on the port specified using its own IP						need a different port for each NodePort service\
						no load balancing between nodes since a node is reached directly from outside the cluster\
						NodePort ---> CluserIP ---> Pod\
\
LoadBalancer		-		integrates with an external load balancer so traffic from outside the cluster can get into the cluster\
						When you create a LB service Kubernetes detects the cloud platform and creates a LB in the infrastructure of the Cloud Provider (The LB has its own unique IP, publicly accessible that clients connect to)\
						Both NodePort and ClusterIP services are automatically created.\
						The LB load balances between nodes\
						Load Balancer ---> Worker Node IP ---> NodePort ---> CluserIP ---> Pod\
\
\
ExternalName		-		a service name resolves to an external URL\
\
\
Headless			-		is a ClusterIP service without an IP address\
						has a selector OR has an Endpoint resource\
						The Endpoint resource has a static list of IP address(es)\
						when a pod makes a call to that service(http call, tcp call) the traffic is routed to the Endpoint IP address\
						the DNS entry for the service returns an IP address for each POD (if the POD is in a StatefulSet then each pod gets its own DNS entry)\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Note: \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In a simplified form, the ClusterIP Service tells the client "Let me take care of routing that request for you." In contrast, a headless Service says "Here is a list of all the Pods that I know about and their IP addresses. Send and route your network requests however you want."\
\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\
Scenarios where a Service maybe without a selector\
 - the service points to an external resource, e.g. a database\
 - the service points to a service in a different namespace\
 - the service points to a service in a different cluster\
\
\
How to reach a service\
\
from a pod in the same namespace		-	<service-name>\
from a pod in a different namespace		-	<service-name>.<namespace>.svc.<cluster_dns_domain>   (the dns domain when not specified becomes cluster.local)\cf0 \cb1 \
