\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 Volumes\
\
pod-level					-	emptyDir\
node-level					-	hostPath\
cluster-level\
 - file-sharing				-	nfs\
 - cloud provider specific		-	awsElasticBlockStore, azureFile, azureDisk, gcePersistentDisk\
 - distributed file system		-	glusterfs, cephfs\
 - special-purpose			-	secret, gitRepo\
\
\
emptyDir\
- cannot specify resource consumption limits\
- it has the lifecycle of the pod (very important to remember this, a container restart will not affect this type of volume), pod restart means volume is lost\
- good for apps that use the filesystem for caching information\
\
\
hostPath\
- data is stored physically on the node, it is not replicated to other nodes\
- works for single worker node clusters, since pods always run on the same node OR you force the pod to run on the same node\
- Kubernetes does not restrict which directory on the node is available for hostPath, so using / will expose the system\
- use case is when apps are need some temp storage for state\
- pod restart does not remove the volume or data in it\
\
\
Persistent Volume\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
- a pv is a cluster-wide resource that you can use to store data in a way that it persists beyond the lifetime of a pod\cf7 .\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 - not backed by locally attached storage\
- backed by networked storage\
- access modes		\
	- RWO		- ReadWriteOnce, only one pod can read and write to the volume\
- reclaim policy	\
	- Retain		- retain the volume once the pvc claiming it has been deleted\
	- Delete		- delete the volume once the pvc claiming it has been deleted\
\
\
\
\
PersistentVolumeClaims\
- a pvc needs to be bound to a pv before it can be used in a pod.\
- if a pod is deployed with an unbound pvc then the pod will remain in the pending state\
\
\
\
Storage Class\
- an abstraction of storage that can create volumes dynamically, the pv does not have to exist from before\
- one storage class can be a default\
- if storageClass field is omitted in pvc spec then the default storage class is used\
- if storageClass field is specified in pvc but no value for it is given then a pv must exist\
\
Configuring\
- provisioner				- 		the component which creates PVs on demand\
- reclaimPolicy				-		what to do with dynamically created volumes when the claim is deleted\
- volumeBindingMode		-		whether the PV gets created as soon as the PVC is created OR not until a pod is created which uses the pvcxfcr\
\
\
\
\
DaemonSet\
- a single replica of a pod on every node in the cluster (or on a subset of nodes if there is a selector in the spec)\
- one use case is for collecting information from every node\
- another use case is you want mulitple instances of an app where it is acceptable for each instance to have its own data store\
- cascade=false delete can remove the daemonset without affecting the running pods, good for maintenance tasks\
- Strategies for deployment are \
  - ramped/rolling 	-	release a new version in a rolling update fashion (DEFAULT), scale down old replicaset while scaling up new replicaset, provides service continuity and staggering\
					there is no surge option, since only 1 pod is per node, it is always delete then remove strategy\
  - OnDelete		-	you deploy the update and the controller watches the pods, but does not terminate the pods, it waits until a POD is deleted by another process and then it replaces deleted Pods with Pods from new spec\
\
\
\
StatefulSet\
- provides certain guarantees about the identity of the pods it is managing (predictable names for the pods)\
- provides a startup order and ordered scaling and updating\
- pods in statefulsets retain thier IP addresses on restart\
- each pod can be accessed individually over DNS (each pod gets its own DNS entry) in the form of - \'93pod-name.service-name.namespace.svc.cluster.local\'94\
- for network communication you need to create a headless service\
- USE CASE is for clustered applications\
- volumeClaimTemplates can give each pod its pv, when the pod is replaced the new pod will get the same pv as the previous pod\
