ServiceAccount\
- a ServiceAccount provides an identity for processes that run in a pod, meaning that a sa is used to authenticate machine level processes to get access to the Kubernetes cluster\
- therefore the pod will use the service account to authenticate with the kubernetes api or an external service\
- if a service account is not specified, a pod will use the \'91default\'92 service account for that namespace\
\
- meant to be used by in-cluster Kubernetes-created entities, like pods. (WHY???)\
\
Note: When a service account is created an authentication token for it is created automatically\
\
\
\
ResourceQuota\
- if there is a quota on a namespace then every pod spec needs to include a resource section \
- this allows Kubernetes to compare what the spec needs to be to what is currently in the namespace\
\
Note: Container limit settings are reactive, pods are restarted on breaching the limit. Resource quotas are proactive, they prevent pods from starting up if the pod breaches the limit\
