\cf2 INIT CONTAINERS\
\
- used to prepare a container running in a pod\
- configure things at runtime, e.g. init data in a database, add some things to a shared volume that the application container will have access to later on like clone a git repo\
- app containers will not run till init container complete successfully\
- logs from initContainers remain even after they have exited\
- are run when the pod is replaced\
- if you deploy a Pod spec change to the app container image(s), the app container are replaced but the init containers are not executed again\
\
\
\
\
ROLLOUT and ROLLBACK\
\
Deployment\
- rollout involves creating a new ReplicaSet\
- rollout is not done until a change is done to a POD spec, e.g. scaling up can be done with the current replicaset \
\
- under normal circumstances, a change to the configmap is updated in the pod after a while but the deployment which manages the pod has \'93not\'94 done a rollout and moved to another replicaset, so a rollback cannot be applied (Config objects are mutable)\
- Config objects can be made immutable wherein they are locked into the deployment so the rollout history is available even for config changes\
\
\
- kubernetes restarts failed pods by creating replacement containers but it adds a pause between reach restart. That pause is the backoff time and it increases exponentially\
	10 seconds for first restart\
	20 seconds for second restart\
	40 seconds for third restart\
	up to a maximum of 5 minutes (progressDeadlineSeconds)\
\
\
DaemonSet\
 - only maxUnavailable from rollingUpdate is available\
\
\
StatefulSet\
 - no maxSurge or maxUnavailable settings for StatefulSets, update is always one pod at a time\
 - since pods are managed in order, updates are also managed in order\
 - rollout proceeds backwards from last Pod in the set to the first\
 - \
\
\
Rollouts can be affected by Readiness probes\
\
\
\
HEALTH CHECKS/PROBES\
\
Readiness probe			\
- takes action at the network level\
- if the container is unhealthy it is taken out of the ready state and removed from the list of active pods for a Service\
\
\
Liveness probe\
- takes action at the compute level\
- if the container becomes unhealthy it is replaced with a new one\
- note it is the container not the Pod that is replaced\
- kubernetes will not indefinitely keep restarting/replacing a container\
\
\
\
LOGGING\
\
2 types of Logs\
 - node system logs\
 - container logs\
\
Node System Logs\
 - journalctl -xe -u kubelet\
\
Container Logs\
 - stored as filenames that include namespace, pod and container names in the format \'91pod-name_namespace_container-name-container-id.log\'92\
 - Fluentd adds Pod labels and the image tag as additional metadata\
\
\
Events				-	OpenShift Events in a namespace\
\
\
Operators for logging\
- Cluster Logging operator		-	ClusterLogging Custom Resource, a CR by the name of \'91instance\'92 already exists\
- ElasticSearch Operator		-	\
\
\
Components\
- logstore				-	Elasticsearch\
- collection				-	Fluentd		uses journald as the system log source (log messages from the operating system, container runtime and OpenShift platform) available from \'91systemd journal and /var/log/containers\'92\
- visualization			-	Kibana\
- curation				-	Curator\
- EventRouter			-	forwards events to log of the pod where the event occurred (so events get to cluster logging)\
